{"parse":{"title":"Marriage bar","pageid":17065226,"revid":859003948,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>A <b>marriage bar</b> is the custom and practice of restricting the <a href=\"/wiki/Employment\" title=\"Employment\">employment</a> of <a href=\"/wiki/Marital_status\" title=\"Marital status\">married women</a> in general or in particular <a href=\"/wiki/Profession\" title=\"Profession\">professions</a> or occupations; sometimes the practice called for the termination of employment of a woman on her marriage, especially in teaching, clerical and other occupations, and sometimes widowed women with children were still considered to be married preventing them from being hired.<sup id=\"cite_ref-:1_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:1-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>The practice never had an economic justification, and its rigid application could be disruptive to workplaces. It was justified during depression years as a social policy to find jobs for more family units, but the policy persisted beyond such economic times. The practice was common in some Western countries from the late 19th century to the 1970s. Marriage bars created a disincentive for women to marry, at least until they were ready to give up work, and some women, including <a href=\"/wiki/Ruby_Payne-Scott\" title=\"Ruby Payne-Scott\">Ruby Payne-Scott</a>, kept their marriage secret to keep their jobs. Marriage bars did not affect employment in lower paid jobs, and therefore lowered incentives for women to acquire <a href=\"/wiki/Education\" title=\"Education\">education</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> Marriage bars were widely relaxed in wartime.\n</p><p>Since the 1960s, the practice has widely been regarded as <a href=\"/wiki/Employment_discrimination\" title=\"Employment discrimination\">employment inequality</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Discrimination#Sex.2C_gender.2C_and_gender_identity\" title=\"Discrimination\">sexual discrimination</a>, and has widely been either discontinued or outlawed by <a href=\"/wiki/Anti-discrimination_law\" title=\"Anti-discrimination law\">anti-discrimination laws</a> which may also deal with discrimination based on <a href=\"/wiki/Marital_status\" title=\"Marital status\">marital status</a>. In the <a href=\"/wiki/Netherlands\" title=\"Netherlands\">Netherlands</a>, the marriage bar was removed in 1957,<sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-7\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup> and in <a href=\"/wiki/Republic_of_Ireland\" title=\"Republic of Ireland\">Ireland</a> it was instituted in 1932 and removed in 1973.<sup id=\"cite_ref-8\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-8\">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-9\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-9\">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup> Since 1975, female officers of the <a href=\"/wiki/British_Geological_Survey\" title=\"British Geological Survey\">British Geological Survey</a> no longer have to resign upon getting married.<sup id=\"cite_ref-British_10-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-British-10\">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Types\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Types</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Reasons_given_for_marriage_bars\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Reasons given for marriage bars</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#Exceptions_to_marriage_bars\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Exceptions to marriage bars</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-5\"><a href=\"#Further_information\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">5</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Further information</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Types\">Types</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Marriage_bar&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Types\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Generally, marriage bars can be classified as  the \u201chire bar\u201d preventing the hiring of married women, and the \u201cretain bar\u201d preventing the retention of married workers.<sup id=\"cite_ref-:2_11-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:2-11\">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Marriage bars also meant that often female employees were classified as supplementary staff, rather than permanent. This was the case, for example, at <a href=\"/wiki/Lloyds_Bank\" title=\"Lloyds Bank\">Lloyds Bank</a> until 1949, when the bank abolished its marriage bar.<sup id=\"cite_ref-12\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-12\">&#91;12&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Reasons_given_for_marriage_bars\">Reasons given for marriage bars</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Marriage_bar&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Reasons given for marriage bars\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>A 1946 article in <i><a href=\"/wiki/The_Spectator\" title=\"The Spectator\">The Spectator</a></i>, a British conservative magazine, gave (and dismissed) a few reasons for the implementation of the marriage bars.<sup id=\"cite_ref-:0_13-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:0-13\">&#91;13&#93;</a></sup> Arguments included: women who were married were supported by their husbands, therefore they did not need jobs.<sup id=\"cite_ref-:0_13-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:0-13\">&#91;13&#93;</a></sup> Marriage bars provided more opportunity for those whom proponents viewed as \"actually\" needing employment, such as single women.<sup id=\"cite_ref-:0_13-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:0-13\">&#91;13&#93;</a></sup> Another argument <i>The Spectator</i> makes states unmarried women are more reliable and mobile than married women.<sup id=\"cite_ref-:0_13-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:0-13\">&#91;13&#93;</a></sup> As single women did not have a family or other pressing responsibilities, they were more reliable and flexible than married women.<sup id=\"cite_ref-:0_13-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:0-13\">&#91;13&#93;</a></sup>  The last point made by this magazine involves the turnover rate.<sup id=\"cite_ref-:0_13-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:0-13\">&#91;13&#93;</a></sup> The turnover rate for women in these jobs was high because lots of young single women eventually got married.<sup id=\"cite_ref-:0_13-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:0-13\">&#91;13&#93;</a></sup> Since they did not hold their positions very long, it gave them less of an opportunity for advancement and promotions.<sup id=\"cite_ref-:0_13-7\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:0-13\">&#91;13&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Marriage bars were connected to social and economic fluctuations, for example, after the end of <a href=\"/wiki/World_War_I\" title=\"World War I\">World War I</a>, returning servicemen who wanted jobs, and afterwards the depression in the 1930s, led to the implementation of marriage bars in many professions during the <a href=\"/wiki/Interbellum_period\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Interbellum period\">interbellum period</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-14\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-14\">&#91;14&#93;</a></sup> However, marriage bars were often justified on moral grounds, especially in places where there was a very strong tradition of married women staying at home and being <a href=\"/wiki/Housewives\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Housewives\">housewives</a>, something more common in rich countries, such as, for instance, the <a href=\"/wiki/Netherlands\" title=\"Netherlands\">Netherlands</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-15\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-15\">&#91;15&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Exceptions_to_marriage_bars\">Exceptions to marriage bars</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Marriage_bar&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: Exceptions to marriage bars\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p><i>Women's History Matters</i> states that marriage bars had some exceptions.<sup id=\"cite_ref-:1_1-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:1-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> Contrary to urban areas, rural areas needed teachers so they were willing to hire married women.<sup id=\"cite_ref-:1_1-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:1-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> Schools were also willing to hire women if they could prove that their husbands were \u201cinvalid, insane, or unable to provide for the family\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-:1_1-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:1-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>  Marriage bars were less strict during World War II, because the women were needed again for these jobs.<sup id=\"cite_ref-:1_1-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:1-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> For example, in Montana, 1500 women were welcomed back into the school systems for the duration of World War II only.<sup id=\"cite_ref-:1_1-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:1-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> Around the time of WW ll 87% of school boards  would not hire married women and 70% would not retain a single woman who married. But later on in 1951 18% of the school boards had the \"hire bar\" and 10% had the \"retain bar\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-:2_11-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:2-11\">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup> Marriage bars only applied to educated, middle-class married women, particularly native born white women. Their occupations were that of teaching, and clerical work. These occupations were most needed and required in secondary school education. Meanwhile, lower class women of colour who took jobs in manufacturing, waitressing, and domestic servants were unaffected by marriage bans.<sup id=\"cite_ref-:2_11-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:2-11\">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup> Discrimination against married female teachers in the US was not terminated until 1964 with the passing of the <a href=\"/wiki/Civil_Rights_Act_of_1964\" title=\"Civil Rights Act of 1964\">Civil Rights Act</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-:1_1-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:1-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>The <a href=\"/wiki/BBC\" title=\"BBC\">BBC</a> had a marriage bar between 1932 and 1944, although it was a partial ban and was not fully enforced due to the BBC's ambivalent views on the policy.<sup id=\"cite_ref-16\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-16\">&#91;16&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Marriage_bar&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap mw-references-columns\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-:1-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-:1_1-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-:1_1-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-:1_1-2\"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-:1_1-3\"><sup><i><b>d</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-:1_1-4\"><sup><i><b>e</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-:1_1-5\"><sup><i><b>f</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-:1_1-6\"><sup><i><b>g</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://montanawomenshistory.org/must-a-woman-give-it-all-up-when-she-marries-the-debate-over-employing-married-women-as-teachers/\">\"<span style=\"padding-left:0.2em;\">\"</span>Must a woman . . . give it all up when she marries?\": The Debate over Employing Married Women as Teachers\"</a>. <i>Women's History Matters</i><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">2015-11-04</span></span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=Women%27s+History+Matters&amp;rft.atitle=%22Must+a+woman+.+.+.+give+it+all+up+when+she+marries%3F%22%3A+The+Debate+over+Employing+Married+Women+as+Teachers&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fmontanawomenshistory.org%2Fmust-a-woman-give-it-all-up-when-she-marries-the-debate-over-employing-married-women-as-teachers%2F&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AMarriage+bar\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\">\"JSTOR\". <a href=\"/wiki/JSTOR\" title=\"JSTOR\">JSTOR</a>&#160;<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//www.jstor.org/stable/23196053\">23196053</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=JSTOR&amp;rft_id=%2F%2Fwww.jstor.org%2Fstable%2F23196053&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AMarriage+bar\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span> <span style=\"display:none;font-size:100%\" class=\"error citation-comment\">Missing or empty <code style=\"color:inherit; border:inherit; padding:inherit;\">&#124;url=</code> (<a href=\"/wiki/Help:CS1_errors#cite_web_url\" title=\"Help:CS1 errors\">help</a>)</span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/bitesize/standard/history/scotland_britain_1880_now/employment_women/revision/3/\">\"BBC - Standard Grade Bitesize History - Women and work&#160;: Revision, Page 3\"</a>. <i>bbc.co.uk</i><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">8 October</span> 2015</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=bbc.co.uk&amp;rft.atitle=BBC+-+Standard+Grade+Bitesize+History+-+Women+and+work+%3A+Revision%2C+Page+3&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.bbc.co.uk%2Fbitesize%2Fstandard%2Fhistory%2Fscotland_britain_1880_now%2Femployment_women%2Frevision%2F3%2F&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AMarriage+bar\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-4\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Borjas, George J. (2007). <i>Labor Economics</i> (4th ed.). London: McGraw-Hill. p.&#160;402. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0073402826\" title=\"Special:BookSources/978-0073402826\">978-0073402826</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Labor+Economics&amp;rft.place=London&amp;rft.pages=402&amp;rft.edition=4th&amp;rft.pub=McGraw-Hill&amp;rft.date=2007&amp;rft.isbn=978-0073402826&amp;rft.aulast=Borjas&amp;rft.aufirst=George+J.&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AMarriage+bar\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-5\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-5\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><i>The Economics of Imperfect Labor Markets: Second Edition</i>, by Tito Boeri, Jan van Ours, pp. 105</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-6\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-6\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://rm.coe.int/CoERMPublicCommonSearchServices/DisplayDCTMContent?documentId=090000168045ae0e\">Dutch gender and LGBT-equality policy, 2013-16</a></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-7\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-7\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.unece.org/fileadmin/DAM/Gender/publication/Netherlands_2015_Review_BPFA_Report_of_the_Netherlands_Government.pdf\">2015 Review BPFA Report of the Netherlands Government</a></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-8\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-8\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\">Patterson, Rachel A. <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://web.archive.org/web/20151008154655/https://martindale.cc.lehigh.edu/sites/martindale.cc.lehigh.edu/files/Patterson.pdf\">\"Women of Ireland: Change Toward Social and Political Equality in the 21s